==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mar
<hw>Mar</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A small lake. See
<er>Mere</er>.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mar</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mar
<hw>Mar</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Marred</conjf> <pr>(m⟦aum⟧rd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Marring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>marren</ets>,
<ets>merren</ets>, AS. <ets>merran</ets>, <ets>myrran</ets> (in comp.),
to obstruct, impede, dissipate; akin to OS. <ets>merrian</ets>, OHG.
<ets>marrjan</ets>, <ets>merran</ets>; cf. D. <ets>marren</ets>,
<ets>meeren</ets>, to moor a ship, Icel. <ets>merja</ets> to bruise,
crush, and Goth. <ets>marzjan</ets> to offend. Cf. <er>Moor</er>,
<pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make defective; to do injury
to, esp. by cutting off or defacing a part; to impair; to disfigure; to
deface.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I pray you <qex>mar</qex> no more trees with wiring love songs in
their barks.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But mirth is <qex>marred</qex>, and the good cheer is lost.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ire, envy, and despair⟦br⟧
Which <qex>marred</qex> all his borrowed visage.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To spoil; to ruin.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧It makes us, or it
<xex>mars</xex> us.⟦rdquo⟧ ⟦ldquo⟧Striving to mend, to <xex>mar</xex>
the subject.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mar</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mar
<hw>Mar</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mark or blemish made by bruising,
scratching, or the like; a disfigurement.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mara</ent>⟦br⟧
